{"id":"1804.04253","submitter":"Hatef Sadeghi","authors":"Norah Algethami, Hatef Sadeghi, Sara Sangtarash, Colin J Lambert","title":"The conductance of porphyrin-based molecular nanowires increases with\n  length","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1021/acs.nanolett.8b01621","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  High electrical conductance molecular nanowires are highly desirable\ncomponents for future molecular-scale circuitry, but typically molecular wires\nact as tunnel barriers and their conductance decays exponentially with length.\nHere we demonstrate that the conductance of fused-oligo-porphyrin nanowires can\nbe either length independent or increase with length at room temperature. We\nshow that this negative attenuation is an intrinsic property of\nfused-oligo-porphyrin nanowires, but its manifestation depends on the electrode\nmaterial or anchor groups. This highly-desirable, non-classical behaviour\nsignals the quantum nature of transport through such wires. It arises, because\nwith increasing length, the tendency for electrical conductance to decay is\ncompensated by a decrease in their HOMO-LUMO gap. Our study reveals the\npotential of these molecular wires as interconnects in future molecular-scale\ncircuitry.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 11 Apr 2018 23:12:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-01"}
